77
00:08:48,508 --> 00:08:50,442
Yeah, I guess you're right.

78
00:08:50,510 --> 00:08:52,944
Well, I have books, telescopes, star charts.

79
00:08:53,013 --> 00:08:54,947
You could borrow some stuff.

80
00:08:55,015 --> 00:08:59,008
We could go out,
look at the sky... t-tonight.

81
00:08:59,085 --> 00:09:01,280
Maybe sometime. Sure.

82
00:09:02,355 --> 00:09:03,947
Okay.

83
00:09:06,059 --> 00:09:09,722
Well, I'll just be hauling these enormous
grocery bags upstairs now.

84
00:09:09,796 --> 00:09:11,889
Okay.

85
00:09:11,965 --> 00:09:13,557
Okay.

86
00:09:45,765 --> 00:09:47,756
What are you doing?

87
00:09:47,834 --> 00:09:49,597
Oh.

88
00:09:49,669 --> 00:09:51,432
People watching.

89
00:09:52,505 --> 00:09:54,769
Anyone in particular?

90
00:09:56,109 --> 00:09:58,577
Just people.

91
00:10:04,117 --> 00:10:08,645
Listen, I'm going out with some friends
tonight, later, if you want to come.

92
00:10:08,721 --> 00:10:10,655
Oh.

93
00:10:10,723 --> 00:10:14,090
<i>They're people,
so you might want to... watch them.</i>

94
00:10:14,160 --> 00:10:16,321
Uh-huh.

95
00:10:16,396 --> 00:10:18,626
But if not, you know, that's fine.

96
00:10:18,698 --> 00:10:22,964
No, I want to go,
but, um, I– I don't think I can.

97
00:10:23,036 --> 00:10:25,971
- Okay, if you're busy.
- No.

98
00:10:26,039 --> 00:10:30,669
I mean, it's not a date. It's just a little
moving-in celebration, you know.

99
00:10:30,743 --> 00:10:32,301
When?

100
00:10:32,378 --> 00:10:34,812
8:00. 8:00-ish.

101
00:10:34,881 --> 00:10:36,815
Uh-huh.

102
00:10:36,883 --> 00:10:38,817
Look, there's no pressure.

103
00:10:38,885 --> 00:10:42,218
I'll just knock on your door
on my way out, and if you can, you can.

104
00:10:43,289 --> 00:10:45,120
<i>- Okay.
- Yeah?</i>

105
00:10:45,191 --> 00:10:46,852
<i>- Yeah.
- Okay.</i>

106
00:11:40,079 --> 00:11:41,706
Adam?

107
00:11:45,852 --> 00:11:47,342
<i>Adam.</i>

108
00:12:20,053 --> 00:12:22,044
<i>- See you later!
- Good night!</i>

109
00:12:28,828 --> 00:12:31,820
I'm sorry I didn't come out with your friends.

110
00:12:31,898 --> 00:12:33,798
No problem.

111
00:12:34,867 --> 00:12:36,892
I get kind of overloaded.

112
00:12:39,172 --> 00:12:41,538
I have something to show you.

113
00:12:44,377 --> 00:12:46,368
Come in. Come in.

114
00:12:51,718 --> 00:12:53,845
Oh, my!

115
00:12:57,824 --> 00:13:00,452
<i>You said you want to know more about space.</i>

116
00:13:01,894 --> 00:13:04,761
<i>Because it looks like this
people think of it as still...</i>

117
00:13:04,831 --> 00:13:06,765
<i>even though we know its expanding.</i>

118
00:13:06,833 --> 00:13:09,768
<i>All parts of the universe
are moving away from one another...</i>

119
00:13:09,836 --> 00:13:12,270
<i>most of them faster than the speed of light,
except for-</i>

120
00:13:12,338 --> 00:13:15,273
I thought nothing went faster
than the speed of light.

121
00:13:15,341 --> 00:13:19,334
<i>Right, right. Nothing goes
through space faster, but space itself g-</i>

122
00:13:19,412 --> 00:13:22,813
<i>Do you know about the Big Bang?</i>

123
00:13:22,882 --> 00:13:26,045
A little. In the beginning, God crea–

124
00:13:26,119 --> 00:13:29,555
<i>The inflation theory says the Big Bang came
from as little as a 20-pound chunk of space...</i>

125
00:13:29,622 --> 00:13:31,385
about 14 billion years ago...

126
00:13:31,457 --> 00:13:35,393
<i>that expanded to the size of the universe
in 10 to the minus-39 seconds.</i>

127
00:13:35,461 --> 00:13:37,588
Ten to the minus-39?

128
00:13:37,664 --> 00:13:39,598
A decimal point, 39 zeros, and then a one.

129
00:13:39,666 --> 00:13:42,829
That's the fraction of a second
in which the universe was formed.

130
00:13:42,902 --> 00:13:45,370
<i>That's billions and billions of times
faster than light.</i>

131
00:13:45,438 --> 00:13:49,033
Ooh, that's... fast.

132
00:13:50,376 --> 00:13:52,037
Yeah.

133
00:13:57,317 --> 00:13:59,182
Wow!

134
00:13:59,252 --> 00:14:03,211
These are all pictures of stars and galaxies
that have been traveling away from us...

135
00:14:03,289 --> 00:14:06,986
for hundreds of millions or billions of years.

136
00:14:07,060 --> 00:14:11,656
<i>But that's still nearby compared to
most of the universe that we'll never see.</i>

137
00:14:11,731 --> 00:14:13,562
Never?

138
00:14:13,633 --> 00:14:17,330
<i>Well, things that move apart faster than light
can't ever see one another...</i>

139
00:14:17,403 --> 00:14:19,701
because the light from one
never catches up to the other.

140
00:14:19,772 --> 00:14:21,706
<i>After the Big Bang...</i>

141
00:14:21,774 --> 00:14:24,265
the expansion of the universe slowed down.

142
00:14:24,344 --> 00:14:26,403
But then, after seven billion years...

143
00:14:26,479 --> 00:14:28,709
<i>for some reason it speeded up again...</i>

144
00:14:28,781 --> 00:14:31,113
<i>and it's been speeding up ever since.</i>

145
00:14:31,184 --> 00:14:35,245
Someday everything you see here
will disappear forever.

146
00:14:36,689 --> 00:14:38,623
<i>And eventually the night sky...</i>

147
00:14:38,691 --> 00:14:41,353
will be almost completely dark.

148
00:14:46,632 --> 00:14:49,226
That's kinda sad.

149
00:14:50,403 --> 00:14:52,064
Sad?

150
00:14:52,138 --> 00:14:53,571
Hmm.

151
00:14:57,844 --> 00:15:01,439
I have been talking too much, so–

152
00:15:01,514 --> 00:15:04,005
No, it's... fascinating.

153
00:15:04,083 --> 00:15:07,052
- But I talk too much when I get excited.
- No, really.

154
00:15:07,120 --> 00:15:09,054
It's– It's amazing.

155
00:15:09,122 --> 00:15:12,057
Well, I could tell you quickly
about M-brane theory.

156
00:15:12,125 --> 00:15:14,559
Oh, no, it's okay. Maybe next time.

157
00:15:14,627 --> 00:15:16,618
Okay. It's very speculative.

158
00:15:18,064 --> 00:15:19,827
Well, I should go.

159
00:15:22,602 --> 00:15:25,036
Good night, Beth.

160
00:15:25,104 --> 00:15:27,095
Good night.

161
00:15:30,343 --> 00:15:33,676
Thanks. I love your planetarium.

162
00:15:33,746 --> 00:15:36,044
Oh. You're welcome.

163
00:15:46,459 --> 00:15:48,393
Oh, I could have waited, Daddy.

164
00:15:48,461 --> 00:15:51,396
Not another day.
I wanted you out of that rat trap for five years.

165
00:15:51,464 --> 00:15:54,922
- They were mice.
- But I was right, wasn't I? You love it.

166
00:15:55,001 --> 00:15:58,198
It's okay. It's not like the Village.
I've only met one person so far.

167
00:15:58,271 --> 00:16:01,206
- It's new.
- He did have a planetarium
in his living room though.

168
00:16:01,274 --> 00:16:03,139
You were in someone's living room.

169
00:16:03,209 --> 00:16:05,143
He's cute. He lives in the building.

170
00:16:05,211 --> 00:16:07,145
Whatever happened to Rich Lippmann?

171
00:16:07,213 --> 00:16:08,840
Not going there.

172
00:16:08,915 --> 00:16:12,180
But what was the name of his company?
Founder's Fund?

173
00:16:13,186 --> 00:16:14,813
Okay. Okay.

174
00:16:14,887 --> 00:16:17,287
So, your neighbor's an astronomer?

175
00:16:17,356 --> 00:16:20,291
No, he's an electronic engineer,
whatever that means.

176
00:16:20,359 --> 00:16:23,624
- But he hasn't even said hello to me
since the first time, so–
- So, he's an idiot.

177
00:16:23,696 --> 00:16:25,391
No, it's me.

178
00:16:25,465 --> 00:16:29,902
Didn't anyone tell you and Mom
that only children are emotional retards...

179
00:16:29,969 --> 00:16:33,200
spoilt, too trusting and unequipped to cope?

180
00:16:33,272 --> 00:16:35,206
What were you thinking?

181
00:16:35,274 --> 00:16:37,265
That we had one perfect child.

182
00:16:40,947 --> 00:16:42,414
How's school?

183
00:16:42,482 --> 00:16:44,575
We just started.

184
00:16:44,650 --> 00:16:47,915
"The course of civilization is a race
between catastrophe and education."

185
00:16:47,987 --> 00:16:50,547
- John F. Kennedy.
- I know.

186
00:16:50,623 --> 00:16:52,591
Well, if you marry an investment banker...

187
00:16:52,658 --> 00:16:54,592
you could do whatever you want.

188
00:16:54,660 --> 00:16:57,390
Rich Lippmann is a dick, Daddy.
Can we leave it at that?

189
00:16:57,463 --> 00:16:59,431
Don't say "dick" to your father.

190
00:16:59,499 --> 00:17:03,060
No one's perfect, Bethy. That's all I'm saying.

191
00:17:05,037 --> 00:17:08,234
<i>But their sensor systems have detected
an error in analyzing space radiation.</i>

192
00:17:08,307 --> 00:17:11,435
Adam, I'm having lunch.

193
00:17:11,511 --> 00:17:13,445
- Speak English.
- I'm sorry.

194
00:17:13,513 --> 00:17:15,447
You see, the Star Tracker system is–

195
00:17:15,515 --> 00:17:20,953
No. No more background radiation
black holes or Mars robots.

196
00:17:21,020 --> 00:17:23,079
Lunchtime is for guy talk.

197
00:17:23,155 --> 00:17:27,683
Two guys talking about women,
the weather and such. You got it?

198
00:17:30,329 --> 00:17:32,889
- But the Star Tracker system–
- No.

199
00:17:38,271 --> 00:17:40,262
Hmm.

200
00:17:40,339 --> 00:17:42,273
A woman moved into 3A.

201
00:17:42,341 --> 00:17:45,401
<i>All right. Now, that's lunch talk.</i>

202
00:17:45,478 --> 00:17:47,912
So?

203
00:17:47,980 --> 00:17:49,914
So, that's all.

204
00:17:49,982 --> 00:17:53,349
Come on. A woman moved into 3A.

205
00:17:53,419 --> 00:17:55,546
She looked–

206
00:17:55,621 --> 00:17:57,555
She looked nice.

207
00:17:57,623 --> 00:18:00,091
Good. Good!

208
00:18:01,360 --> 00:18:03,328
- You gonna meet her?
- I did.

209
00:18:03,396 --> 00:18:04,988
You did?

210
00:18:05,064 --> 00:18:08,056
We did laundry. She came to my apartment.

211
00:18:08,134 --> 00:18:11,069
- She did?
- Yeah, I told her something about space.

212
00:18:11,137 --> 00:18:14,072
- Oh, Jesus. How'd she take it?
- She liked it.

213
00:18:14,140 --> 00:18:15,573
She–

214
00:18:15,641 --> 00:18:18,633
Well, bless my stars. You gonna see her again?

215
00:18:18,711 --> 00:18:20,975
I see her almost every day.

216
00:18:21,047 --> 00:18:22,981
You talk to her again?

217
00:18:23,049 --> 00:18:25,449
No.

218
00:18:25,518 --> 00:18:27,452
Adam.

219
00:18:27,520 --> 00:18:29,454
You're the man.

220
00:18:29,522 --> 00:18:32,616
You have to start the conversation.
Ask her out. Take her to dinner.

221
00:18:32,692 --> 00:18:35,126
I can't do that. H-How–

222
00:18:36,762 --> 00:18:38,696
Hmm.

223
00:18:38,764 --> 00:18:41,494
This jackass locked himself out of his car.

224
00:18:41,567 --> 00:18:43,865
Figures he can cuss me out on the phone.

225
00:18:43,936 --> 00:18:47,428
Well, he ought to be chilled by now.

226
00:18:47,506 --> 00:18:49,736
Harlan–

227
00:18:51,177 --> 00:18:53,111
Follow through, young man.

228
00:18:53,179 --> 00:18:55,170
Follow through.

229
00:18:57,550 --> 00:19:00,678
<i>Are you and Mom still going to Barbados this year?</i>

230
00:19:00,753 --> 00:19:03,847
