735
00:57:00,063 --> 00:57:03,931
<i>- You said it would help if we showed our support.
- You had to tell her that.</i>

736
00:57:04,001 --> 00:57:05,901
Your father's right. You have work.

737
00:57:05,969 --> 00:57:09,496
<i>Mom, I'm covered at work.
I'm coming. I need to be there for you.</i>

738
00:57:09,573 --> 00:57:12,133
What are you accused of, Mr. Buchwald?

739
00:57:18,916 --> 00:57:22,352
I'm accused of trying to help a friend.
That's what I'm accused of.

740
00:57:24,087 --> 00:57:26,749
<i>- Beth's Uncle Eric-
- Eric Cooper.</i>

741
00:57:26,823 --> 00:57:29,519
- made his daughter, Jennifer,
C.F.O. of his company.
- But she's qualified, right?

742
00:57:29,593 --> 00:57:31,720
- I mean, she went to Wharton.
- Yes. She's qualified.

743
00:57:31,795 --> 00:57:33,786
Uncle Eric's not really my uncle.

744
00:57:33,864 --> 00:57:36,594
<i>He's an old friend of Daddy's,
and Jennifer is his daughter.</i>

745
00:57:36,667 --> 00:57:39,101
She's young. She made a few mistakes.

746
00:57:39,169 --> 00:57:41,535
<i>I carried them over from one year to the next...</i>

747
00:57:41,605 --> 00:57:43,937
<i>made her look a little better,
even to her own father.</i>

748
00:57:44,007 --> 00:57:47,534
<i>It wasn't even a hard call to make,
but now they all think they've uncovered Enron.</i>

749
00:57:47,611 --> 00:57:50,580
- Could you go to jail?
- Adam!

750
00:57:50,647 --> 00:57:54,083
No. I'm glad you asked.

751
00:57:54,151 --> 00:57:57,143
Bethy, I'm not going anywhere.

752
00:57:59,957 --> 00:58:02,619
Any more questions, Mr. Prosecutor?

753
00:58:02,693 --> 00:58:05,253
No.

754
00:58:05,329 --> 00:58:08,560
See? He fits right in.

755
00:58:08,632 --> 00:58:11,465
<i>You put him on the spot,
confronted him, pushed him.</i>

756
00:58:11,535 --> 00:58:13,696
Well, I– I didn't understand what he was saying.

757
00:58:13,770 --> 00:58:17,433
Maybe that's not his fault. Monday
he goes on trial, in case you didn't get that.

758
00:58:17,507 --> 00:58:19,532
You don't talk about going to jail!

759
00:58:19,609 --> 00:58:22,271
- It seemed like the important thing.
- The important thing?

760
00:58:22,346 --> 00:58:24,337
All of a sudden you know what's important?

761
00:58:24,414 --> 00:58:26,712
You can't say two words
on how you feel about anything...

762
00:58:26,783 --> 00:58:28,774
but you know what's important to my family.

763
00:58:28,852 --> 00:58:31,878
- I-I do–
- You know, my father's not some criminal, okay?

764
00:58:31,955 --> 00:58:34,947
- Oh, okay.
- Just forget it!

765
00:58:35,025 --> 00:58:38,825
- Beth?
- I'm going home! And please don't follow me!

766
00:59:07,057 --> 00:59:08,991
May I come in?

767
00:59:12,596 --> 00:59:14,587
I'm sorry.

768
00:59:14,664 --> 00:59:16,928
It's some chocolate.

769
00:59:17,000 --> 00:59:19,468
I'm not Forrest Gump, you know.

770
00:59:20,537 --> 00:59:23,597
Of course not. I didn't me–

771
00:59:23,673 --> 00:59:27,473
- Was that a joke? Are you joking?
- Well, I can joke.

772
00:59:28,545 --> 00:59:30,809
I'm sorry.

773
00:59:30,881 --> 00:59:33,372
I–

774
00:59:33,450 --> 00:59:37,045
I took it out on you.
I'm just–just scared for my father.

775
00:59:44,561 --> 00:59:47,325
You can apologize too, you know.

776
00:59:47,397 --> 00:59:49,991
Well, you said it was your fault.

777
00:59:51,868 --> 00:59:53,733
I got an interview.

778
00:59:53,804 --> 00:59:55,931
You did?

779
00:59:56,006 --> 00:59:58,975
Halloran Industries, research and engineering...

780
00:59:59,042 --> 01:00:01,476
for space communication and exploration.

781
01:00:01,545 --> 01:00:04,070
Adam, that's– that's perfect!

782
01:00:04,147 --> 01:00:07,173
Break out the chocolate.
Let's go get some champagne.

783
01:00:07,250 --> 01:00:09,480
Well, no, it's just an interview.

784
01:00:09,553 --> 01:00:14,183
There's a saying in my family:
It's never too early to drink the champagne.

785
01:00:23,300 --> 01:00:25,291
You'd be good at this job, right?

786
01:00:25,368 --> 01:00:27,928
So all you gotta do is let 'em know it.

787
01:00:28,004 --> 01:00:29,938
That's all? That's impossible.

788
01:00:30,006 --> 01:00:31,769
When is it?

789
01:00:31,842 --> 01:00:34,675
It– February 3– 17 days.

790
01:00:34,744 --> 01:00:36,735
Right. So that's how long you got.

791
01:00:36,813 --> 01:00:40,544
You gotta learn it during the day,
and then I'll help you at night.

792
01:00:40,617 --> 01:00:42,551
They'll think I'm a freak.

793
01:00:43,653 --> 01:00:47,054
Fine. Whatever you say.

794
01:00:47,124 --> 01:00:49,115
Beth?

795
01:00:50,393 --> 01:00:52,327
Beth?

796
01:00:56,733 --> 01:00:59,133
Come on.

797
01:01:00,937 --> 01:01:02,871
Whoa!

798
01:01:09,746 --> 01:01:11,737
<i>In most interview situations...</i>

799
01:01:11,815 --> 01:01:14,477
<i>the greeting is done in the standing position.</i>

800
01:01:14,551 --> 01:01:17,987
<i>Simple greeting. "Hello. Nice to meet you."</i>

801
01:01:18,054 --> 01:01:20,921
<i>Basic greeting. "Hello. My name is Jason.</i>

802
01:01:20,991 --> 01:01:23,391
<i>Nice to meet you."</i>

803
01:01:23,460 --> 01:01:25,553
<i>Mr. Buchwald, how do you plead?</i>

804
01:01:25,629 --> 01:01:27,563
Not guilty, Your Honor.

805
01:01:27,631 --> 01:01:29,565
<i>Involved greeting.</i>

806
01:01:29,633 --> 01:01:33,034
<i>"Hello. You must be Ms. Austen.
My name is Jason. Nice to meet you."</i>

807
01:01:33,103 --> 01:01:35,094
<i>Mr. Raki?</i>

808
01:01:39,075 --> 01:01:41,009
I'm Elizabeth Buchwald.

809
01:01:41,077 --> 01:01:44,012
I'll be interviewing you
for the job we discussed over the phone.

810
01:01:44,080 --> 01:01:46,913
- Phone?
- Nice to meet you?

811
01:01:46,983 --> 01:01:48,974
Oh, right, right.

812
01:01:50,687 --> 01:01:53,212
Eyes. Please, step into my office.

813
01:01:53,290 --> 01:01:55,224
<i>Make it a goal of your interview...</i>

814
01:01:55,292 --> 01:01:58,921
<i>to mention each of your strengths at least once.</i>

815
01:01:58,995 --> 01:02:02,089
The items listed as assets
are really expenses...

816
01:02:02,165 --> 01:02:05,566
<i>covered up in order to increase
the earnings statement of the company.</i>

817
01:02:11,875 --> 01:02:13,809
<i>Eye contact.</i>

818
01:02:13,877 --> 01:02:16,710
<i>One way to get around
the poor eye contact dilemma...</i>

819
01:02:16,780 --> 01:02:20,477
<i>is to have the candidate look
at the interviewer's forehead.</i>

820
01:02:20,550 --> 01:02:23,644
<i>Practice is needed, however,
because it will still require an effort...</i>

821
01:02:23,720 --> 01:02:26,280
<i>to remember to look at a forehead.</i>

822
01:02:33,797 --> 01:02:35,731
- Beth?
- No!

823
01:02:35,799 --> 01:02:37,767
Just once more, please.

824
01:02:37,834 --> 01:02:41,861
Adam, can't you think about anyone but yourself,
even for a minute?

825
01:02:42,872 --> 01:02:44,806
- I'm sorry.
- No.

826
01:02:44,874 --> 01:02:49,334
Okay.

827
01:02:49,412 --> 01:02:53,280
Tell me something about
your previous work experience, Mr. Raki.

828
01:02:55,085 --> 01:02:59,385
<i>At your last job, how much of the work
did you perform independently?</i>

829
01:02:59,456 --> 01:03:01,447
<i>How much as a team?</i>

830
01:03:01,524 --> 01:03:04,584
Now, you've testified that your relationship
with the Cooper family...

831
01:03:04,661 --> 01:03:06,856
is personal as well as professional,
isn't that right?

832
01:03:06,930 --> 01:03:11,424
Yes. Eric Cooper and I
have been associated for over 30 years.

833
01:03:11,501 --> 01:03:14,493
He's become a close friend.
But that doesn't mean–

834
01:03:14,571 --> 01:03:16,505
Would you tell the court a little...

835
01:03:16,573 --> 01:03:19,667
about your relationship
with Jennifer Cooper?

836
01:03:20,844 --> 01:03:23,335
She's a wonderful young woman.

837
01:03:23,413 --> 01:03:26,678
I've known her her– her whole life.

838
01:03:26,750 --> 01:03:31,187
<i>Isn't it true that you'd be eager to help
Jennifer with any problem she was having?</i>

839
01:03:31,254 --> 01:03:33,654
<i>- Yes.
- Out of your affection for the family, of course.</i>

840
01:03:33,723 --> 01:03:35,520
Sure.

841
01:03:35,592 --> 01:03:38,925
Now, Mr. Buchwald,
would you feel compelled to help Jennifer...

842
01:03:38,995 --> 01:03:40,986
to preserve your own reputation?

843
01:03:41,064 --> 01:03:43,726
No.

844
01:03:43,800 --> 01:03:46,792
Did you have an affair with Ms. Cooper in 2001?

845
01:03:46,870 --> 01:03:50,306
<i>- Objection, Your Honor.
- Mr. Buchwald opened the door, Your Honor.</i>

846
01:03:50,373 --> 01:03:53,137
I understand the evidence, counselor.
Overruled.

847
01:03:53,209 --> 01:03:55,143
Please answer the question.

848
01:03:58,081 --> 01:04:00,140
Yes. Briefly.

849
01:04:00,216 --> 01:04:03,379
<i>So, Jennifer had every reason to believe...</i>

850
01:04:03,453 --> 01:04:05,978
<i>that you would help her with this problem.</i>

851
01:04:06,056 --> 01:04:07,990
That had noth–

852
01:04:11,127 --> 01:04:15,757
The one had nothing to do with the other.

853
01:04:16,900 --> 01:04:18,834
<i>Nothing.</i>

854
01:06:32,068 --> 01:06:34,298
<i>All rise.</i>

855
01:06:41,744 --> 01:06:43,735
<i>Be seated.</i>

856
01:06:50,053 --> 01:06:52,317
<i>Mr. Raki.</i>

857
01:06:52,388 --> 01:06:55,687
Hello. You must be Doug Breindel. I'm Adam Raki.

858
01:06:55,758 --> 01:06:57,749
- Pleased to meet you.
- Come in.

859
01:07:14,244 --> 01:07:18,146
<i>Six inches by Sunday morning
before this storm moves its way through-</i>

860
01:07:18,214 --> 01:07:20,444
<i>So it is a major storm.</i>

861
01:07:21,951 --> 01:07:24,579
- Beth?
- Adam, is Beth there?

862
01:07:24,654 --> 01:07:26,588
No, she isn't.

863
01:07:26,656 --> 01:07:29,784
Marty pled guilty.

864
01:07:29,859 --> 01:07:31,793
There's some discretion in sentencing.

865
01:07:31,861 --> 01:07:33,795
The–The hearing is tomorrow.

866
01:07:33,863 --> 01:07:37,128
We may have to make statements,
but she isn't answering her cell.

867
01:07:37,200 --> 01:07:39,191
I called the school,
but they– she wasn't there.

868
01:07:39,269 --> 01:07:41,260
Do you know when she'll be home?

869
01:07:41,337 --> 01:07:44,272
No. I thought– I was waiting for–

870
01:07:44,340 --> 01:07:48,401
Adam, please. Can you check her calendars,
see if there's anywhere I can reach her?

871
01:07:48,478 --> 01:07:50,412
Okay.

872
01:07:58,354 --> 01:08:00,584
Never mind. Marty's coming. I have to go.

873
01:08:00,657 --> 01:08:03,490
They're–They're keeping him overnight.
Tell her to call me.

874
01:08:03,560 --> 01:08:05,585
Tell her to call me right away.

875
01:08:19,409 --> 01:08:21,343
Adam!

876
01:08:21,411 --> 01:08:24,437
I've been thinking about you all afternoon.
How did it go?

877
01:08:26,249 --> 01:08:29,548
I forgot my phone. How did the interview go?

878
01:08:35,892 --> 01:08:38,656
Okay, you're right.

879
01:08:38,728 --> 01:08:42,528
- Right?
- My father and I arranged for us to meet.

880
01:08:43,600 --> 01:08:45,465
You arranged?

881
01:08:45,535 --> 01:08:47,526
I knew they were gonna be at the theater.

882
01:08:47,604 --> 01:08:49,538
They really wanted to meet you.

883
01:08:49,606 --> 01:08:52,507
Now, will you please tell me what happened?

884
01:08:54,344 --> 01:08:56,278
You lied?

885
01:08:57,447 --> 01:08:59,381
Just a little.

886
01:09:03,920 --> 01:09:06,150
Ha-ha-ha! Fooled you!

887
01:09:06,222 --> 01:09:10,682
Dumb Adam!
Dumb, dumb, dumb, dumb, dumb, dumb!

888
01:09:10,760 --> 01:09:13,024
<i>Dumb, dumb, dumb, dumb Adam!</i>

889
01:09:13,096 --> 01:09:16,532
Adam, I didn't– I– I'm sorry. I–

890
01:09:17,700 --> 01:09:19,565
- Adam, please just calm down.
- No, I hate you!

891
01:09:19,636 --> 01:09:22,503
- No!
- I hate you! I hope your father goes to jail forever.

892
01:09:22,572 --> 01:09:26,372
- I hate you!
- What?

893
01:09:26,442 --> 01:09:28,535
<i>He's guilty! Your mother called.</i>

894
01:09:28,611 --> 01:09:31,671
And he's a liar like you,
and he's going to jail. I hate you!

895
01:09:34,083 --> 01:09:38,179
You're a child, Adam.
Fuck Asperger's. You're a fucking child.

896
01:09:45,795 --> 01:09:47,729
Liar!

897
01:10:01,944 --> 01:10:05,004
A long time ago, when I told Grandpa Morris...

898
01:10:05,081 --> 01:10:07,049
that I wanted to get married...

899
01:10:07,116 --> 01:10:10,449
he said Marty was great...

900
01:10:10,520 --> 01:10:12,784
but that he was an angles guy.

901
01:10:12,855 --> 01:10:14,846
What does that mean?

902
01:10:14,924 --> 01:10:19,361
That he was a guy who plays the angles...

903
01:10:19,429 --> 01:10:22,421
in business, love.

904
01:10:22,498 --> 01:10:25,228
He even said...

905
01:10:25,301 --> 01:10:27,963
he might wind up in jail someday.

906
01:10:29,272 --> 01:10:32,173
And I told him he didn't understand Marty...

907
01:10:32,241 --> 01:10:35,836
and that even if he ended up in jail for life...

908
01:10:35,912 --> 01:10:38,506
I would never regret marrying him.

909
01:10:40,349 --> 01:10:43,250
And I don't.

910
01:10:48,324 --> 01:10:50,315
We have to help him now, Beth.

911
01:10:52,295 --> 01:10:55,958
Tell the judge who your father is in your life...

912
01:10:56,966 --> 01:10:58,900
who he's always been.

913
01:11:00,103 --> 01:11:02,037
Whatever...

914
01:11:04,107 --> 01:11:06,667
bad decisions he's made.

915
01:11:13,683 --> 01:11:15,947
Okay.

916
01:11:16,018 --> 01:11:18,851
Okay, Mom.

917
01:11:43,880 --> 01:11:47,077
<i>Now, I read that planets
are lined up across the sky...</i>

918
01:11:47,150 --> 01:11:51,484
like they haven't been in 30,000 years.

919
01:11:51,554 --> 01:11:53,488
Uh-huh.

920
01:11:55,758 --> 01:11:58,124
You didn't get the job you were going for?

921
01:11:58,194 --> 01:12:00,059
No.

922
01:12:00,129 --> 01:12:02,563
That why you so down?

923
01:12:02,632 --> 01:12:05,260
<i>- Hell, I've lost more jobs than-
- No.</i>

924
01:12:05,334 --> 01:12:09,293
- Beth and I broke up.
- Oh.

925
01:12:09,372 --> 01:12:12,068
She lied. She lied, and I found out about it.

926
01:12:12,141 --> 01:12:14,473
I can't trust her anymore.

927
01:12:21,551 --> 01:12:23,542
These all seem fine.

928
01:12:25,454 --> 01:12:28,480
Now, before I went into the service...

929
01:12:28,558 --> 01:12:31,857
I met a girl who made me a promise.

930
01:12:31,928 --> 01:12:36,331
When I came back,
she was right there waiting for me.

931
01:12:36,399 --> 01:12:39,630
But I found out
she hadn't quite kept her promise...

932
01:12:39,702 --> 01:12:43,399
so I put some things in a bag and I left.

933
01:12:43,472 --> 01:12:46,236
Never spoke to her again.

934
01:12:46,309 --> 01:12:49,278
Though sometimes the wanting to was–

935
01:12:49,345 --> 01:12:53,839
was like a live animal
clawing at my chest from the inside.

936
01:12:53,916 --> 01:12:56,680
<i>Thirty-five years.</i>

937
01:12:56,752 --> 01:13:00,313
She's the only picture in my head...

938
01:13:00,389 --> 01:13:03,825
can still stop me in broad daylight...

939
01:13:03,893 --> 01:13:08,262
and make me curse myself
for a stubborn old fool.

940
01:13:11,534 --> 01:13:14,901
It's not rocket science.

941
01:13:14,971 --> 01:13:18,873
I'm saying you need to talk to the girl
one more time, that's all.

942
01:13:18,941 --> 01:13:21,705
No. I don't know.

943
01:13:22,945 --> 01:13:26,142
Liars is all you're
gonna run across in this world.

944
01:13:26,215 --> 01:13:30,379
A man has got to learn the difference
between just plain liars...

945
01:13:30,453 --> 01:13:33,422
and liars worth lovin'.

946
01:13:33,489 --> 01:13:35,423
Hmm?

947
01:13:39,829 --> 01:13:41,888
Harlan? If you called that girl...

948
01:13:41,964 --> 01:13:44,899
couldn't you stop cursing yourself
for a stubborn old fool...

949
01:13:44,967 --> 01:13:47,128
even if you still had to be old?

950
01:13:57,146 --> 01:13:59,080
Be seated.

951
01:14:01,751 --> 01:14:04,811
<i>This court sentences you
to a prison term of five years...</i>

952
01:14:04,887 --> 01:14:08,152
<i>24 months to be served
in a federal corrections institute...</i>

953
01:14:08,224 --> 01:14:12,183
followed by three years of mandatory probation.

954
01:14:12,261 --> 01:14:16,027
<i>As per your plea agreement,
you'll have one week to settle your affairs.</i>

955
01:14:16,098 --> 01:14:18,566
<i>Report to the Corrections Department...</i>

956
01:14:18,634 --> 01:14:21,603
<i>Monday, February 9, at 9:00 a.m.</i>

957
01:14:22,638 --> 01:14:25,163
<i>Adjourned.</i>

958
01:14:31,514 --> 01:14:34,506
You have one new message.

959
01:14:34,583 --> 01:14:36,710
Adam, this is Rebecca.

960
01:14:36,786 --> 01:14:40,449
Marty was sentenced
to two years in prison today.

961
01:14:40,523 --> 01:14:44,186
<i>Of course we're all very upset, but Beth-</i>

962
01:14:45,227 --> 01:14:47,195
<i>Anyway, we're going home to Westchester-</i>

963
01:14:47,263 --> 01:14:49,288
<i>211 Richmond Road, Bedford Hills.</i>

964
01:14:49,365 --> 01:14:52,857
<i>You have the number.
I- I thought you should know where she is.</i>

965
01:14:52,935 --> 01:14:55,927
For months, all they wanted was
for me to give them Eric Cooper.

966
01:14:58,074 --> 01:15:01,566
<i>"Do not go about as a talebearer
amongst your people."</i>

967
01:15:01,644 --> 01:15:03,908
At least I don't have to pack, right, Becky?

968
01:15:03,980 --> 01:15:05,914
We always pack too much.

969
01:15:05,982 --> 01:15:08,678
This time, just the toothbrush.

970
01:15:11,921 --> 01:15:13,855
Excuse me.

971
01:15:16,225 --> 01:15:18,455
Let's talk for a minute.

972
01:15:40,916 --> 01:15:43,180
Ah, Bethy. Bethy.

973
01:15:44,720 --> 01:15:47,814
Your mother's gonna need your help.

974
01:15:47,890 --> 01:15:49,824
Yeah, I know.

975
01:15:53,329 --> 01:15:56,765
<i>There are things you do,
there are things you have to do...</i>

976
01:15:56,832 --> 01:15:59,892
<i>and... you make your choices.</i>

977
01:15:59,969 --> 01:16:02,233
<i>You live with them.</i>

978
01:16:02,304 --> 01:16:07,207
You and your mother will never want
for anything. I've made arrangements.

979
01:16:07,276 --> 01:16:09,801
In two years I'll be back home...

980
01:16:09,879 --> 01:16:11,813
and this will all be over.

981
01:16:13,416 --> 01:16:15,407
One more thing, about Adam?

982
01:16:19,021 --> 01:16:20,955
He's not for you.

983
01:16:22,758 --> 01:16:26,455
<i>It's not his fault,
but he's-he's more like your child...</i>

984
01:16:26,529 --> 01:16:29,498
<i>than- than anything else.</i>

985
01:16:29,565 --> 01:16:33,501
<i>He'll never be the kind of man
that you can admire, that you can look up to.</i>

986
01:16:33,569 --> 01:16:36,561
<i>And it's not fair that he should hope
for something that's- that's-</i>

987
01:16:36,639 --> 01:16:39,233
<i>that's... impossible.</i>

988
01:16:41,577 --> 01:16:45,377
People with Asperger's get married.

989
01:16:45,448 --> 01:16:48,008
- They have families.
- Married?

990
01:16:49,919 --> 01:16:52,888
He lives in another world.

991
01:16:52,955 --> 01:16:55,947
You don't need to make
that kind of compromise, Beth.

992
01:16:58,327 --> 01:17:01,728
Um–You know this is the best thing.

993
01:17:04,400 --> 01:17:06,391
You do know that, Bethany.

994
01:19:00,115 --> 01:19:03,846
Beth?

995
01:19:03,919 --> 01:19:06,979
Beth Buchwald!

996
01:19:07,056 --> 01:19:10,423
<i>Beth?</i>

997
01:19:10,492 --> 01:19:13,586
Beth Buchwald!

998
01:19:13,662 --> 01:19:15,596
<i>- Beth Buchwald?
- Oh, God.</i>

999
01:19:20,035 --> 01:19:22,162
I'll get him.

1000
01:19:22,238 --> 01:19:24,433
Beth?

1001
01:19:24,506 --> 01:19:27,475
<i>- Adam!
- Be–</i>

1002
01:19:38,754 --> 01:19:40,745
We–we have to talk again.

1003
01:19:42,424 --> 01:19:45,154
You scared me.
I thought you were gonna hit me.

1004
01:19:46,495 --> 01:19:48,622
No, I would never, ever do that.

1005
01:19:51,934 --> 01:19:54,596
The job was gone.

1006
01:19:54,670 --> 01:19:57,070
They hired someone for the job...

1007
01:19:57,139 --> 01:20:00,302
but they have another one in an observatory.

1008
01:20:00,376 --> 01:20:03,470
They said I was just what they needed.

1009
01:20:03,545 --> 01:20:06,981
It starts in April,
but it's in Flintridge, California.

1010
01:20:07,049 --> 01:20:09,643
I want you to come with me.

1011
01:20:09,718 --> 01:20:11,948
I could work, and you could write...

1012
01:20:12,021 --> 01:20:14,922
<i>and you wouldn't have to teach anymore.</i>

1013
01:20:14,990 --> 01:20:17,322
Hello, Mr. Buchwald. I came– Oh.

1014
01:20:17,393 --> 01:20:19,657
I'm sorry you have to go to prison.

1015
01:20:19,728 --> 01:20:22,356
I came to ask Beth to come to California with me.

1016
01:20:22,431 --> 01:20:25,832
I'd be engineering microchips
for satellite guidance systems.

1017
01:20:25,901 --> 01:20:28,631
I have a job in Flintridge, California.

1018
01:20:28,704 --> 01:20:31,195
That's fine. Congratulations, Adam.

1019
01:20:31,273 --> 01:20:34,504
- But Beth won't be able to go with you.
- What?

1020
01:20:34,576 --> 01:20:37,272
- The family needs her. She's needed here.
- I need her.

1021
01:20:37,346 --> 01:20:39,337
I can't go without her.

1022
01:20:39,415 --> 01:20:42,407
- Well, I'm sorry, Adam, but she can't go.
- No.

1023
01:20:42,484 --> 01:20:44,418
- You can't do that.
- Bethy. Bethy.

1024
01:20:44,486 --> 01:20:46,249
- You can't speak for me.
- We agreed.

1025
01:20:46,322 --> 01:20:47,983
- You don't make my decisions!
- We agreed!

1026
01:20:48,057 --> 01:20:50,287
- We're standing in the middle of the st–
- I don't care!

1027
01:20:50,359 --> 01:20:52,919
- Calm down. Calm down!
- Your own choices– Liar! Cheater!

1028
01:20:52,995 --> 01:20:55,555
Nothing will ever be the same! Nothing!
I'm going now.

1029
01:20:55,631 --> 01:20:58,657
- And I don't care what you think!
- Don't go! You can't!

1030
01:20:58,734 --> 01:21:01,862
- Let go. Let go of me.
- Get off of me!

1031
01:21:01,937 --> 01:21:03,734
<i>- Adam!
- Oh! God!</i>

1032
01:21:05,307 --> 01:21:07,241
<i>Adam!</i>

1033
01:21:10,512 --> 01:21:13,003
- But you're coming to California?
- No!

1034
01:21:13,082 --> 01:21:15,710
- I mean, home, to the city!
- You're not coming to California?

1035
01:21:15,784 --> 01:21:18,184
- Maybe! I don't know! I'll think about it!
- Oh, okay.

1036
01:21:18,253 --> 01:21:21,518
<i>Mom! I'm gonna take the car.
I'll leave it at the station.
- Beth!</i>

1037
01:21:21,590 --> 01:21:24,115
Come back here!

1038
01:22:10,205 --> 01:22:12,196
It didn't go well?

1039
01:22:18,614 --> 01:22:20,605
What did he say?

1040
01:22:20,682 --> 01:22:22,673
He wouldn't even see me.

1041
01:22:23,786 --> 01:22:27,722
I waited in the visiting room for an hour.

1042
01:22:27,790 --> 01:22:31,817
And finally a guard came and told me
that he wasn't coming out.

1043
01:22:33,495 --> 01:22:35,656
Your mother said he wasn't ready.

1044
01:22:35,731 --> 01:22:38,996
<i>I thought if I actually went.</i>

1045
01:22:39,067 --> 01:22:42,525
I didn't think that he wouldn't even see me.

1046
01:22:44,673 --> 01:22:47,233
- What are you gonna do?
- What do you mean?

1047
01:22:48,977 --> 01:22:53,346
We're going, right? We're getting on a plane
tomorrow and going to California.

1048
01:22:55,818 --> 01:22:57,945
You should pack. You haven't packed at all.

1049
01:22:59,021 --> 01:23:02,149
Can you give me a minute? Okay?

1050
01:23:05,527 --> 01:23:08,462
Just leave me alone for a while.

1051
01:23:43,432 --> 01:23:48,495
<i>I'm not sure.
I mean, I should be sure, shouldn't I?</i>

1052
01:23:48,570 --> 01:23:50,561
Do you know what you want?

1053
01:23:52,074 --> 01:23:55,976
We'll never have a moment
where we look into each other's eyes...

1054
01:23:56,044 --> 01:23:59,241
and know exactly...

1055
01:23:59,314 --> 01:24:01,805
what the other person's feeling.

1056
01:24:03,652 --> 01:24:06,086
The idea of that wouldn't even make sense to him.

1057
01:24:06,154 --> 01:24:08,714
He's never told me that he loves me.

1058
01:24:12,694 --> 01:24:15,424
I don't know what it would mean to him if he did.

1059
01:24:18,166 --> 01:24:21,624
Yes. Feeling loved is very important...

1060
01:24:21,703 --> 01:24:23,898
but...

1061
01:24:23,972 --> 01:24:26,736
loving, my precious girl–

1062
01:24:28,644 --> 01:24:30,771
that's the necessity.

1063
01:24:36,018 --> 01:24:38,452
Mom, I gotta go.
I'll– I'll talk to you tomorrow.

1064
01:24:38,520 --> 01:24:41,080
Okay?

1065
01:24:43,458 --> 01:24:45,483
I love you, Beth.

1066
01:24:48,730 --> 01:24:51,631
<i>Adam?</i>

1067
01:24:51,700 --> 01:24:54,430
Why do you want me
to go to California with you?

1068
01:24:54,503 --> 01:24:57,995
What? What do you mean?

1069
01:24:58,073 --> 01:25:00,803
Why do you want me to go?

1070
01:25:02,477 --> 01:25:04,604
Um–

1071
01:25:10,018 --> 01:25:12,509
You, um–

1072
01:25:12,588 --> 01:25:15,785
You a-are...

1073
01:25:15,857 --> 01:25:19,315
like a part of me.

1074
01:25:24,466 --> 01:25:26,400
Um...

1075
01:25:29,705 --> 01:25:32,333
and, um...

1076
01:25:34,109 --> 01:25:38,068
I n– I need you...

1077
01:25:38,146 --> 01:25:40,341
uh, to–

1078
01:25:42,851 --> 01:25:44,785
to, uh...

1079
01:25:44,853 --> 01:25:47,754
help find a place to live...

1080
01:25:47,823 --> 01:25:50,986
and to learn how to get to work and...

1081
01:25:51,059 --> 01:25:54,119
to understand what it means
when people say crazy stuff...

1082
01:25:54,196 --> 01:25:57,256
and, um...

1083
01:25:57,332 --> 01:25:59,664
I couldn't go without you.

1084
01:26:10,879 --> 01:26:12,813
I'm sorry.

1085
01:26:16,084 --> 01:26:18,018
I can't go.

1086
01:26:22,791 --> 01:26:26,249
If you want me to go because...

1087
01:26:26,328 --> 01:26:28,558
you can't go without me, I–

1088
01:26:31,433 --> 01:26:34,027
I can't go.

1089
01:28:22,010 --> 01:28:24,535
- You sure about this?
- I have to go.

1090
01:28:24,613 --> 01:28:27,013
I have to go alone.

1091
01:28:27,082 --> 01:28:29,846
Give me that.

1092
01:28:32,921 --> 01:28:35,719
Hey, I want you to know...

1093
01:28:35,791 --> 01:28:37,782
I made that call.

1094
01:28:42,931 --> 01:28:45,832
It took me a while to find her...

1095
01:28:47,636 --> 01:28:49,866
but we're–we're gonna meet up.

1096
01:28:52,374 --> 01:28:55,866
- The woman's even more stubborn than I am.
- Oh, yeah?

1097
01:28:58,313 --> 01:29:01,180
I'm just trying to say "thank you," damn it.

1098
01:29:03,351 --> 01:29:05,376
You're welcome, Harlan.

1099
01:29:34,950 --> 01:29:37,441
<i>Actually,
the best image resolution is achieved...</i>

1100
01:29:37,519 --> 01:29:41,182
<i>by multiple smaller telescopes
called interferometers.</i>

1101
01:29:41,256 --> 01:29:44,054
<i>Interferometers combine light waves...</i>

1102
01:29:44,125 --> 01:29:46,389
collected from the same source.

1103
01:29:46,461 --> 01:29:50,625
Um, a star, for instance, and the–
the waves form an interference pattern...

1104
01:29:50,699 --> 01:29:53,896
as they add together, or cancel out,
add together, cancel out.

1105
01:29:53,969 --> 01:29:56,904
It's what we call constructive interference,
or destructive interference...

1106
01:29:56,972 --> 01:29:59,202
so that the light from two or more telescopes...

1107
01:29:59,274 --> 01:30:03,870
can produce a brighter image
than one alone.

1108
01:30:03,945 --> 01:30:05,879
Um–

1109
01:30:08,116 --> 01:30:13,748
But sometimes it's best
just to look up at the night sky.

1110
01:30:15,891 --> 01:30:18,655
Thank you. Thank you so much, Mr. Raki.

1111
01:30:18,727 --> 01:30:20,820
All right. We'll be heading out.

1112
01:30:20,896 --> 01:30:22,830
Watch your step.

1113
01:30:24,299 --> 01:30:27,291
Adam. The top one's for you.

1114
01:30:27,369 --> 01:30:29,303
Um–

1115
01:30:35,243 --> 01:30:37,507
Oh, Carol?

1116
01:30:37,579 --> 01:30:41,515
Um, would you like me to help you with those?

1117
01:30:41,583 --> 01:30:43,517
Yeah.

1118
01:30:44,719 --> 01:30:47,085
<i>Thank you.</i>

1119
01:30:55,664 --> 01:30:58,030
- Hey, man.
- Hello, Brian.

1120
01:30:58,099 --> 01:31:00,693
Oh, you still meeting up with everyone later?

1121
01:31:00,769 --> 01:31:02,703
Awesome.

1122
01:31:31,967 --> 01:31:35,334
<i>Dear Adam: Look how far we've come.</i>

1123
01:31:35,403 --> 01:31:37,337
<i>Love, Beth.</i>

1124
01:31:51,853 --> 01:31:54,321
<i>Adam, his mother and his father...</i>

1125
01:31:54,389 --> 01:31:56,380
<i>were a family of talking raccoons...</i>

1126
01:31:56,458 --> 01:31:59,586
<i>who lived in Central Park
in the middle of New York City.</i>

1127
01:31:59,661 --> 01:32:03,097
<i>They didn't really belong there,
but there they were.</i>

